******
[2] EpiCore Global Surveillance Project response
Date: Sun 22 Oct 2017
Source: EpiCore Global Surveillance Project [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]

The information on brucellosis in veterinary students of the National University of Asunción is true. It was related to contact with diseased goats that were already sacrificed. The scope of the event is being investigated. The case is being investigated not only by authorities of the Ministry of Health but also by the Public Prosecutor's Office, being judicialized to clarify the fact.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Global Surveillance Project
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED thanks the EpiCore Global Surveillance Project member for this comment.

ProMED would like more information regarding the number of cases and what symptoms occurred. With the caprine source, _Brucella melitensis_ is the likely organism. It is unfortunate that the authorities at the school were apparently not forthcoming about the infection. That "power corrupts and absolute power corrupts absolutely" is certainly a true adage. It is unfortunate that this event and bullying and other abuses of power may be in the graduate medical/veterinary worlds, like the current sexual abuse issues in the entertainment industry, another "dirty little secret". - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5397373,63307.]
